#          Axis 25 — TOML Parsing — to Go).
# Library: github.com/BurntSushi/toml v1.2.1
#          ("BurntSushi/toml" — "TOML parser for Golang with
#           reflection" — Andrew Gallant (BurntSushi on
#           GitHub) + community.  Distinct from toml (R689,
#           Rust Axis 25 opener) and from pelletier/go-toml
#           (alternative Go TOML library by Thomas Pelletier)
#           by being:
#              1. TOML 1.0 SPEC COMPLIANT — implements TOML
#                 v1.0.0 spec finalized 2021.  Distinct from
#                 the older 0.x versions of BurntSushi/toml
#                 (which targeted TOML pre-1.0).
#              2. struct-TAG MAPPING — Go structs map to TOML
#                 via `toml:"field_name"` struct tags:
#                   type Config struct {
#                       Title    string   `toml:"title"`
#                       Owner    Owner    `toml:"owner"`
#                       Database Database `toml:"database"`
#                   }
#                   var cfg Config
#                   _, err := toml.DecodeFile("config.toml", &cfg)
#                   // or:
#                   md, err := toml.Decode(text, &cfg)
#                   // md.Keys() returns parsed keys
#              3. MetaData RETURN — toml.Decode returns
#                 MetaData alongside the decoded struct;
#                 MetaData.Keys() + MetaData.IsDefined()
#                 + MetaData.Undecoded() let callers
#                 inspect which fields were present in input.
#                 Distinct from encoding/json + encoding/yaml
#                 (no equivalent metadata).
#              4. NATIVE Go TIME PARSING — TOML datetime types
#                 (offset-datetime, local-datetime, local-
#                 date, local-time) decode directly into
#                 Go's time.Time (with proper timezone
#                 handling).  Distinct from Rust toml-rs
#                 which uses toml::value::Datetime (separate
#                 from chrono).
#              5. INDENT CONTROL via toml.Encoder.Indent —
#                 set indentation string for emitted TOML.
#              6. PURE Go — no Cgo; works on all Go platforms.
#                 Same minimalist philosophy as BurntSushi's
#                 other libraries (ripgrep — wait, ripgrep is
#                 Rust; the Go-side equivalent is BurntSushi/
#                 freegrep — but the libraries follow consistent
#                 design).
#              7. STRICT MODE via toml.DecodeStrict —
#                 errors on unknown fields (similar to
#                 yaml.UnmarshalStrict).  Useful for config
#                 validation.
#              8. encoding/json COMPATIBILITY — implements
#                 the same Marshaler / Unmarshaler interfaces
#                 used by encoding/json (TextMarshaler
#                 / TextUnmarshaler), so types like
#                 net.IP / time.Time / url.URL automatically
#                 round-trip.
#              9. WIDELY ADOPTED — used by Hugo (since v0.20),
#                 kelseyhightower/confd, Caddy (some configs),
#                 the Cargo equivalent for Go (was used by
#                 gopkg.in tooling), shopify/sarama (Kafka
#                 client), and many others.
#             10. ANDREW-GALLANT / BurntSushi ECOSYSTEM
#                 PROVENANCE — Andrew Gallant (BurntSushi)
#                 is one of the most prolific Rust + Go
#                 developers; maintains:
#                   * ripgrep (Rust) — fast grep replacement
#                                       (90k+ stars)
#                   * BurntSushi/toml (Go) — TOML parser   (THIS)
#                   * BurntSushi/aho-corasick (Rust) — string searching
#                   * BurntSushi/regex-automata (Rust) — regex internals
#                   * rust-lang/regex (Rust) — primary Rust regex
#                                               crate maintainer
#                   * BurntSushi/walkdir (Rust) — directory walker
#                   * BurntSushi/quickcheck (Rust) — property testing
#                   * BurntSushi/xsv (Rust) — CSV tool
#                 BurntSushi crosses languages — most well-known
#                 Rust libraries plus a few Go libraries.  Andrew
#                 is a former Rust core team member.  Distinct
#                 from David Tolnay (Rust serde), Sean McArthur
